storical_data/search_historic_data_stations_e.html?searchType=stnName&timeframe=1&txtStationName=guelph+turfgrass&searchMethod=contains&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=2016&Month=8&Day=7&selRowPerPage=25\n| title = Guelph Turfgrass\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = 7 August 2016\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160819233958/http://climate.weather.gc.ca/historical_data/search_historic_data_stations_e.html?searchType=stnName&timeframe=1&txtStationName=guelph+turfgrass&searchMethod=contains&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=2016&Month=8&Day=7&selRowPerPage=25\n| archive-date = August 19, 2016\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref><ref name=\"February 2017\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=2006-12-15%7C2017-04-29&dlyRange=2006-09-28%7C2017-04-29&mlyRange=2006-12-01%7C2006-12-01&StationID=45407&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2017&selRowPerPage=25&Line=3&searchMethod=contains&Month=2&Day=1&txtStationName=guelph&timeframe=2&Year=2017\n| title = Daily Data Report for February 2017\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = 30 April 2017\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181117104931/http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=2006-12-15%7C2017-04-29&dlyRange=2006-09-28%7C2017-04-29&mlyRange=2006-12-01%7C2006-12-01&StationID=45407&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnName&optLimit=yearRange&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2017&selRowPerPage=25&Line=3&searchMethod=contains&Month=2&Day=1&txtStationName=guelph&timeframe=2&Year=2017\n| archive-date = November 17, 2018\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n| date            = August 2010\n}}\n\n==Economy==\nThe city of Guelph's diversified economy helped Guelph obtain the country's lowest unemployment rate at 4.2 per cent in 2011<ref name=\"guelphmercury1\"/> and at 3.9 per cent in February 2016.<ref name=\"Young\"/> The great diversity in the types of employers is a significant factor too; the city is not dependent on a single industry. The workforce participation rate of 72% was the best in Canada in December 2015 according to BMO senior economist Robert Kavcic. The job growth of more than 9 per cent at the same time was also of great value to the community.<ref>{{cite news |last=Babad |first=Michael |date=January 11, 2016 |title=Welcome to Guelph, Ont., pop. 121,688 and Canada\u2019s jobs powerhouse |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/top-business-stories/welcome-to-guelph-ont-pop-121688-and-canadas-jobs-powerhouse/article28100361/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |access-date=January 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231152936/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/top-business-stories/welcome-to-guelph-ont-pop-121688-and-canadas-jobs-powerhouse/article28100361// |archive-date=December 31, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the time, the BMO economist also rated Guelph as the top city in Canada for those looking for work.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/01/13/best-cities-for-work-canada-bmo_n_8970958.html |title=Canada's Best City To Find A Job? Guelph, Ontario, According To BMO |last=Tencer |first=Daniel |date=January 13, 2016 |website=The Huffington Post Canada |publisher=The Huffington Post |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |quote=The small city about {{cvt|90|km|disp=sqbr}} west of Toronto topped the list for its robust job growth, population inflows, a puny 4.2 percent jobless rate and the highest share of the population that is working |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223184657/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/01/13/best-cities-for-work-canada-bmo_n_8970958.html |archive-date=December 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Over subsequent months, the rate increased steadily and the jobless rate was at a more typical 5.9% by October 2017, compared to 5.1% in Kitchener-Waterloo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statcan.gc.ca/tables-tableaux/sum-som/l01/cst01/lfss03g-eng.htm|title=Labour force characteristics, seasonally adjusted, by census metropolitan area (3 month moving average) (Kitchener-Cambridge-Waterloo (Ont.), Brantford (Ont.), Guelph (Ont.))|publisher=Statistics Canada|website=www.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=November 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205324/https://www.statcan.gc.ca/tables-tableaux/sum-som/l01/cst01/lfss03g-eng.htm|archive-date=November 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The rate in June 2018 had decreased to 4.5%.<ref name=\"Lovell\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/8736177-university-degree-may-not-be-ticket-to-job-in-guelph/|title=University degree may not be ticket to job in Guelph|first=Jessica|last=Lovell|date=July 11, 2018|publisher=Guelph Mercury|access-date=July 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714200011/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/8736177-university-degree-may-not-be-ticket-to-job-in-guelph/|archive-date=July 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/180706/dq180706a-eng.htm|title=The Daily \u2014 Labour Force Survey, June 2018|first=Government of Canada, Statistics|last=Canada|website=www150.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=July 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714221856/https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/180706/dq180706a-eng.htm|archive-date=July 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By December 2018, [[Statistics Canada|StatsCan]] was indicating an unemployment rate of only 2.3%, down from 4% in November, and the lowest in Canada at that time.<ref name=\"Guelph Mercury Tribune\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/9124082-guelph-top-city-in-canada-for-employment-bmo-report/?s=n1|title=Guelph top city in Canada for employment: BMO report|date=January 15, 2019|publisher=Guelph Mercury Tribune|quote=Guelph is up 20 spots from the same time period in 2017|access-date=January 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116045908/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/9124082-guelph-top-city-in-canada-for-employment-bmo-report/?s=n1|archive-date=January 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe overall economy of the Guelph \"region\" (including the city and the townships of [[Guelph/Eramosa]] and [[Puslinch, Ontario]]) grew at an average of 3.5% per year over the previous five years and was expected to be 2.1% in 2019 and also in 2020 according to the [[Conference Board of Canada]]'s August 2019 report. Guelph's real gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 3.6% per cent in 2018, the highest among medium-sized cities in Canada. \"Although economic growth is poised to moderate in 2019, Guelph will maintain its place as one of Canada\u2019s economic growth leaders,\" the report predicted.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-leads-canadian-medium-sized-cities-in-key-economic-marker-1627473 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808201701/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-leads-canadian-medium-sized-cities-in-key-economic-marker-1627473 |date=August 8, 2019 }}, Guelph leads Canadian medium-sized cities in key economic marker</ref>\n\n===Manufacturing and education sectors===\nManufacturing is the leading sector of the economy of the city with the most significant sector being auto parts manufacturing.<ref name=\"Young\"/> The [[Conference Board of Canada]]'s August 2019 report stated that the Guelph region's manufacturing was experiencing significant growth, averaging 5.9% over the past five years and expected to be 4.2% in 2019.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\"/>\n\n[[Linamar]] is the city's leader in this sector, with 22 manufacturing plants. The company has received government funding for expansion that would create additional jobs, most recently in 2015 ($101 million)<ref>{{cite web |title=Linamar gets $101 million from Ontario, Ottawa, to create 1,200 jobs |date=January 12, 2015 |first=Robert |last=Benzie |publisher=[[Toronto Star]] |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2015/01/12/101_government_funds_to_linamar_to_create_1200_jobs.html |access-date=January 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117011805/https://www.thestar.com/business/2015/01/12/101_government_funds_to_linamar_to_create_1200_jobs.html |archive-date=January 17, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in 2018 ($99 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/8072818-guelph-s-linamar-to-receive-99-million-from-feds-province/?s=n1|title=Guelph's Linamar to receive $99 million from feds, province|first=Chris|last=Seto|date=January 15, 2018|publisher=Guelph Mercury|access-date=January 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116194141/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/8072818-guelph-s-linamar-to-receive-99-million-from-feds-province/?s=n1|archive-date=January 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The latter would create 1,500 additional jobs and maintain 8,000 others in the Canadian operation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2018/01/15/linamar-to-launch-750-million-expansion-with-help-from-ottawa-ontario.html |title=Linamar to launch $750-million expansion with help from Ottawa, Ontario |publisher=Toronto Star |date=January 15, 2018 |first=Josh |last=Wingrove |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730015956/https://www.thestar.com/business/2018/01/15/linamar-to-launch-750-million-expansion-with-help-from-ottawa-ontario.html |archive-date=July 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to research completed by the City of Guelph in 2010, fabricated metal product manufacturing accounted for 26.1% of the types of industries, followed by machinery manufacturing for 12.8% and miscellaneous manufacturing for 10.4%.<ref name=\"guelph.ca\"/> The City's '''Economic Development Strategy''' identified [[life science]], agri-food and biotechnology firms, environmental management and technology companies as growth industries on which to focus economic development activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Focus on Sectors|publisher=City of Guelph|accessdate= March 17, 2008|url=http://www.guelph.ca/business.cfm?subCatID=1350&smocid=1933|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605005127/http://www.guelph.ca/business.cfm?subCatID=1350&smocid=1933|archive-date=2008-06-05|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe City also touts the importance of advanced manufacturing which is its largest employer. The roughly 360 businesses of this type employ approximately 14,755 people (roughly 25% of Guelph's labour force). The category includes \"high precision manufacturing and auto parts assembly to plastic injection moulding machines manufacturing and automation devices. This enables advanced manufacturing to be a strong driver of the local economy.\"<ref name=\"guelph.ca1\"/>\n\nThe second largest industry is Educational services, accounting for 11.3%.<ref name=\"guelph.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://guelph.ca/uploads/ecdev/2010%20Community%20Profile.pdf |title=City of Guelph 2010 Community Profile |publisher=City of Guelph |archivedate=September 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928062452/http://guelph.ca/uploads/ecdev/2010%20Community%20Profile.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Other sectors===\nGuelph is very attractive to the agri-food and biotechnology market sector, according to the City. It was ranked as the top cluster in Ontario and one of the top two in Canada. This sector includes over 90 companies in Guelph-Wellington,  employing approximately 6,500 people.<ref name=\"guelph.ca1\">{{cite web|url=https://guelph.ca/business/economic-development-office/growth-sectors/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318092857/https://guelph.ca/business/economic-development-office/growth-sectors/ |archivedate=March 18, 2013 |title=Growth Sectors |publisher=City of Guelph}}</ref>\n\nThe City encourages movie and television filming. Parts of several productions have been filmed here, including ''[[Agnes of God (film)|Agnes of God]]'' (1985), ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]'' (released in 2017), ''[[11.22.63]]'' (2016) with James Franco, ''[[Total Recall (2012 film)|Total Recall]]'' (2012), ''[[Dream House (2011 film)|Dream House]]'' (2011), ''[[The Heretics]]'' (2017), ''[[Dead Rush]]'' (2016) and episodes of ''[[Murdoch Mysteries]]'' (2013 and 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/search/title|title=IMDb: Most Popular Titles With Location Matching \"Guelph, Ontario, Canada\"|website=IMDb|access-date=July 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720051311/https://www.imdb.com/search/title|archive-date=July 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/5648070-guelph-readies-to-host-tv-and-movie-filmings/ |title=Guelph readies to host TV and movie filmings |date=May 27, 2015 |first=Tony |last=Saxon |publisher=Guelph Mercury |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326065258/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/5648070-guelph-readies-to-host-tv-and-movie-filmings/ |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inbrampton.com/top-5-movies-filmed-in-Brampton |title=Top 5 Movies Filmed in Brampton |website=InBrampton.com |date=December 3, 2016 |first=Jonah |last=Shinuda |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815030404/https://www.inbrampton.com/top-5-movies-filmed-in-brampton |archive-date=August 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Guelph Innovation District===\nAs part of the plan to increase development, City Council voted in late 2017 to buy 98 hectares (243 acres) south of York Street owned by the Provincial government, including part of the property of the former Wellington Detention Centre.<ref name=\"kitchener.ctvnews.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://kitchener.ctvnews.ca/mobile/guelph/guelph-buying-243-acres-of-land-from-province-1.3718649|title=Guelph buying 243 acres of land from province|date=December 12, 2017|publisher=[[CTV News]] Kitchener|access-date=December 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217014923/https://kitchener.ctvnews.ca/mobile/guelph/guelph-buying-243-acres-of-land-from-province-1.3718649|archive-date=December 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After the acquisition, the City would seek one or more developers to buy the property.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> The land actually purchased was only 23% of the long-term plan for development in the entire site bounded by Watson Parkway South, the south border of the city and Victoria Road South.<ref name=\"City of Guelph\">{{cite web|url=https://guelph.ca/2017/09/gid-op54/|title=Guelph Innovation District Secondary Plan now in effect|date=September 5, 2017|publisher=City of Guelph|access-date=December 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217014414/https://guelph.ca/2017/09/gid-op54/|archive-date=December 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://guelph.ca/plans-and-strategies/guelph-innovation-district-york-district-lands/|title=Guelph Innovation District Secondary Plan|publisher=City of Guelph|access-date=December 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217014324/https://guelph.ca/plans-and-strategies/guelph-innovation-district-york-district-lands/|archive-date=December 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the plan to increase development, City Council voted in late 2017 to buy 98 hectares (243 acres) south of York Street owned by the Provincial government, including part of the property of the former Wellington Detention Centre.<ref name=\"kitchener.ctvnews.ca\"/> The actual land purchased was only 23% of the area listed in the long-term plan for development in the entire 436 hectare (1,000 acre) site bounded by Watson Parkway South.<ref name=\"City of Guelph\"/>\n\nThe city decided in late 2018 not to purchase the additional land for economic reasons.<ref>https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7021693-cash-strapped-province-readies-sale-of-guelph-s-storied-jail-lands/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808203924/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7021693-cash-strapped-province-readies-sale-of-guelph-s-storied-jail-lands/ |date=August 8, 2019 }}, Cash-strapped province readies sale of Guelph\u2019s storied jail lands</ref> In 2019, the remaining 362 acres of Ontario government land was listed for sale by the province.<ref>https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/no-price-tag-on-326-acre-guelph-innovation-district-lands-that-the-province-will-sell-this-year-1341104 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808203922/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/no-price-tag-on-326-acre-guelph-innovation-district-lands-that-the-province-will-sell-this-year-1341104 |date=August 8, 2019 }}, No price tag on 326-acre Guelph Innovation District lands that the province will sell this year</ref>\n\n===Employment data===\nAccording to the [[Bank of Montreal]]'s fourth quarter 2018 report, Guelph was the leading city in Canada in terms of job growth and low unemployment.<ref name=\"Guelph Mercury Tribune\"/> In January 2019, the city had the lowest unemployment rate in Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://am1380.ca/guelph-lowest-jobless-rate-canada/ |title=Guelph has lowest jobless rate in Canada |date=February 8, 2019 |publisher=AM1380 |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |quote=Statistics Canada says the Royal City\u2019s 1.9 per cent unemployment rate was down from 2.3 per cent in December. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223131440/http://am1380.ca/guelph-lowest-jobless-rate-canada/ |archive-date=February 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrreporter.com/article/39292-unemployment-rates-by-province-city/ |title=Unemployment rates by province, city |date=February 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223074303/https://www.hrreporter.com/article/39292-unemployment-rates-by-province-city/ |archivedate=February 23, 2019|publisher=HR Reporter}}</ref>\n\nThe 2016 Census indicated a labour force of nearly 76,000, of which about 55% said they worked full-time all year. At the time the data was gathered, 4,610 persons indicated they were unemployed. The top five occupations in terms of the number so employed were Sales and service (16,195), Education, law and social, community and government services (10,205), Business, finance and administration (10,150), Trades, transport and equipment operators and related occupations (9,170) and manufacturing and utilities (8,205).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7976428-top-5-occupations-employing-the-most-guelph-residents/?s=n1|title=Top 5 occupations employing the most Guelph residents|date=December 2, 2017|publisher=Guelph Mercury|access-date=December 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205042720/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7976428-top-5-occupations-employing-the-most-guelph-residents/?s=n1|archive-date=December 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Guelph's published 2016 data was sorting occupations in a different manner. In that report, Professional, Scientific and Technical jobs employed 39,141, Advanced Manufacturing employed 20,735, Retail and Service employed 11,345, Agri-Innovation employed 11,345, Culture and entertainment employed 7,711 and that Distribution, warehousing and wholesale employed 5,909.<ref name=\"guelph.ca2\">{{cite web |url=https://guelph.ca/business/economic-development-office/guelph-quicksheet/ |title=Guelph Quicksheet |publisher=City of Guelph |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716100048/http://guelph.ca/business/economic-development-office/guelph-quicksheet/ |archive-date=July 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe largest private enterprise employers in Guelph (2016) included:<ref name=\"guelph.ca2\"/>\n\n*Linamar Corporation\n*Cargill Meat Solutions\n*Polycon Industries\n*The Co-operators\n*Guelph Manufacturing Group Inc.\n*Blount Canada Ltd.\n\nThe Cooperators was one of the Platinum Winners in Canada's Best Employers 2017 report; the company has been on this list for 14 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lists-and-rankings/best-jobs/best-employers-2017-top-large-companies/ |title=Canada\u2019s Best Employers 2017: The Top 39 Large Companies |date=November 10, 2016 |publisher=[[Rogers Media]] |work=Canadian Business |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616103003/http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lists-and-rankings/best-jobs/best-employers-2017-top-large-companies/ |archive-date=June 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe largest public sector employers (2016) included:\n\n*Upper Grand District School Board\n*University of Guelph\n*City of Guelph\n*Wellington Catholic District School Board\n*Guelph General Hospital\n*Homewood Health Centre\n\nThe University's staffing fell into three categories in 2015: there were 2,600 regular full-time faculty and staff, 1,890 temporary (full-time and part-time) and 3,690 student employees.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uoguelph.ca/info/factsfigures/ |title=Facts and Figures |date=October 2015 |publisher=University of Guelph |archivedate=December 26, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226062117/http://www.uoguelph.ca/info/factsfigures/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> The University was among Canada's Best Employers in 2016 according to [[Forbes]] magazine, making the top 20 in the list.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kathryndill/2016/02/24/canadas-best-employers-2016/ |title=Canada's Best Employers 2016 |date=February 24, 2016 |first=Kathryn |last=Dill |publisher=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115104802/https://www.forbes.com/sites/kathryndill/2016/02/24/canadas-best-employers-2016/ |archive-date=January 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nTwo Guelph companies were among the 2018 winners of the Waterloo Area's Top Employers competition. According to the report, Reid's Heritage Group of Companies, a home builder with 212 full-time employees, \"supports employees who are new mothers with maternity leave top-up payments .... [provides] flexible work hours,  helps employees balance work and their personal commitments with up to 10 paid personal days ... and offers referral bonuses [for staff hires].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://content.eluta.ca/top-employer-reids-heritage-group|title=Top Employer: Reid's Heritage Group of Companies|date=November 23, 2018|website=content.eluta.ca|publisher=Mediacorp Canada Inc|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523203920/https://content.eluta.ca/top-employer-reids-heritage-group|archive-date=May 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Sleeman Breweries Limited, with 991 full-timers, offers \"generous tuition subsidies ... opportunities for the next generation to gain meaningful experience through summer employment and co-op placements ... retirement planning assistance and phased-in work options\" as well as bonuses for salaried staff and profit-sharing for those who are unionized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://content.eluta.ca/top-employer-sleeman|title=Top Employer: Sleeman Breweries Limited|date=November 23, 2018|website=content.eluta.ca|publisher=Mediacorp Canada Inc|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714164850/https://content.eluta.ca/top-employer-sleeman|archive-date=July 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n| title = Historical populations\n| type  = Canada\n|align       = right\n| width       = \n| state       = \n| shading     = \n| percentages = \n| footnote    = <ref name=\"SC11\"/><ref name=\"census2016\"/>\n|1841|1240\n|1851|1860\n|1871|6878\n|1881|9890\n|1891|10537\n|1901|11496\n|[[Canada 1911 Census|1911]]|15175\n|1921|18128\n|1931|21075\n|1941|23074\n|1951|27386\n|1961|39838\n|1971|60087\n|1981|71207\n|1991|87976\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|95821\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|106170\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|114943\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|121688\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|131794\n}}\n\n{{as of|2016|May}}, the population of the actual city was 131,794 according to the 2016 Census, up from 121,688 in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7112026-guelph-posts-big-growth-in-new-census/|title=Guelph posts big growth in new census|first=Doug|last=Hallett|date=February 9, 2017|work=Guelph Mercury|publisher=Metroland News|access-date=December 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205045848/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7112026-guelph-posts-big-growth-in-new-census/|archive-date=December 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The report also indicated a metropolitan area which does not necessarily conform to the official boundaries. The so-called metropolitan area - including Guelph, [[Guelph/Eramosa]] and [[Puslinch, Ontario|Puslinch]] - had a population of 151,984, an increase of 7.7 per cent since 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thespec.com/news-story/7110521-new-census-data-population-of-metropolitan-area-of-guelph-outpaced-national-growth-rate/|title=New census data: Population of metropolitan area of Guelph outpaced national growth rate|date=February 8, 2017|publisher=Metroland News|work=The [[Hamilton Spectator]]|access-date=December 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205094544/https://www.thespec.com/news-story/7110521-new-census-data-population-of-metropolitan-area-of-guelph-outpaced-national-growth-rate/|archive-date=December 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> That made Guelph one of seven in Canada to experience accelerated growth in the previous five years according to [[Statistics Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |date=February 8, 2017 |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-population-growth-stands-out-in-census-531325 |title=Guelph population growth stands out in census |first=Rob |last=O'Flanagan |website=GuelphToday.com |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206005906/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-population-growth-stands-out-in-census-531325 |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGuelph is the third fastest-growing city in Ontario with a 5-year growth of 8.3% from 2011 to 2016. According to the Ontario Places to Grow plan, Guelph's population is projected to be about 144,500 by the year 2021 and 175,000 by 2031.<ref name=\"guelph.ca2\"/> The actual number of residents varies throughout the year because of variations in the University of Guelph student population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guelph.ca/uploads/PDF/Fact_population_growth.pdf |title=Fact Sheet:Population Growth |author=Craig Manley, Manager of Policy Planning |publisher=City of Guelph |archivedate=April 8, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408133343/http://www.guelph.ca/uploads/PDF/Fact_population_growth.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe most common mother tongue in 2016 was [[English language|English]] at 77.2% followed by [[Chinese language|Chinese Languages]] at 2.7%, [[Italian language|Italian]] at 1.7% [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] at 1.3% [[French language|French]] at 1.3% [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] at 1.2%, [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] at 1.2%, [[Spanish language|Spanish]] at 1.1% and [[Polish language|Polish]] at 1%. 1.5% claimed both English and a non-official language as their first language.<ref name=census/>\n\nApproximately 78.2% of residents were [[European Canadians]] in 2016, whereas 18.8% were visible minorities and 3% were aboriginal. The largest visible minority groups in Guelph were South Asian (5%), Chinese (3.2%), Black (2.2%), Filipino (2.2%), Southeast Asian (1.9%), West Asian (1.2%), and Latin American (1.0%).<ref name=census>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3523008&Geo2=CD&Code2=3523&SearchText=guelph&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=0 |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Guelph, City [Census subdivision], Ontario and Wellington, County [Census division], Ontario |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe 2016 Census indicated that 14,430 [[Italian Canadians]] lived in Guelph.<ref name=census/> Many Italians from the south of Italy, particularly from [[Monforte San Giorgio]], had immigrated to the area in the early 1900s, and also in later years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thewardproject.omeka.net/collections/show/4 |title=The Ward Project - Una Presenza Storica: Italian Immigration and St. Patrick's Ward |website=thewardproject.omeka.net |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714164714/https://thewardproject.omeka.net/collections/show/4 |archive-date=July 14, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Historically however, Guelph's population has been principally [[British people|British]] in origin, with 92% in 1880 and 87% in 1921.<ref name=\"encyclopedia\" />\n\nThe city is mostly [[Christianity|Christian]] (61.8%) according to the 2011 Census, almost evenly split among [[Protestants]] and [[Roman Catholics]]. The largest non-Christian religion is Islam (2.6%), followed by [[Buddhism]] (1.9%), Hinduism (1.5%) and Sikhism (1.0%).<ref name=\"statscan\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3523008&Data=Count&SearchText=Guelph&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Religion&B1=All&Custom=&amp;TABID=1|title=NHS Profile, Guelph, CY, Ontario, 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nThe national average for the crime severity index was 70.96 per 100,000 people in 2016 while Guelph's was much lower at 55 per 100,000 people according to a study published by [[Macleans]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7961571-latest-crime-stats-show-guelph-is-losing-ground-as-one-of-canada-s-safest-places-to-live/ |title=Latest crime stats show Guelph is losing ground as one of Canada's safest places to live |date=November 24, 2017 |publisher=Guelph Mercury |access-date=November 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124180049/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7961571-latest-crime-stats-show-guelph-is-losing-ground-as-one-of-canada-s-safest-places-to-live/ |archive-date=November 24, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In this report, Guelph was at about the middle of the statistics, with the worst community, [[North Battleford]], [[Saskatchewan]], at 353 per 100,000 people and nearby Kitchener-Waterloo at 61. More specific data was also provided:\n\n* Violent crime severity index: 49 per 100,000 people compared to 75.25 for the national index.\n* Homicide rate: The city had only one homicide in 2016 for a rate of 0.76 per 100,000 people, compared to the national average of 1.68.\n* Assault rate: Guelph was at 181.87 versus the national average of 370\n* Sexual assault rate: This aspect was quite high with 64.22 per 100,000 people compared to the national rate of 56.6. \n* Robbery rate: Guelph had 21.91 per 100,000 people, much lower than the national average of 60.9.\n* Fraud: This aspect has increased notably since 1996; it was at 260.67 per 100,000 people in 2016, versus the national rate of 299.05.\n* Drug offences: The city is well below the national average in all categories. \n* Youth Criminal Justice Act offences: The rate was 8.31 per 100,000 in Guelph, substantially lower than the national average of 16.74.\n\nThe 2017 Index showed a 15% increase to 64 per 100,000 people, still well below the national index. Much of the increase was in property crime and sexual assaults. Reporting of the latter type of crimes was up by up 42.7%. This may not indicate the actual increase in the number of sexual assault incidents, as theorized by Chief of Police Jeff DeRuyter. He told a reporter that \"We are seeing an increase in sexual assault reporting, and that\u2019s a positive, because we\u2019ve always believed the reporting of sexual assault was under-reported.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/8761239-crime-up-in-guelph-statistics-canada-says/ |title=Crime up in Guelph, Statistics Canada says |date=July 26, 2018 |publisher=Guelph Mercury Tribune |author=Graeme McNaughton |accessdate=January 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728110329/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/8761239-crime-up-in-guelph-statistics-canada-says/ |archive-date=July 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019, the Chief of Police is former RCMP inspector Gordon Cobey, who replaced Jeff DeRuyter who retired after 35 years of service with the Guelph Police Service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-police-service-has-a-new-chief-of-police-1202007|title=Guelph Police Service has a new Chief of Police|date=January 18, 2019|publisher=Guelph Today|accessdate=April 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407182917/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-police-service-has-a-new-chief-of-police-1202007|archive-date=April 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> DeRuyter had been Chief since 2015, when he replaced Bryan Larkin who went on to head the [[Waterloo Regional Police Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/police-chief-looks-back-on-career-while-looking-forward-to-retirement-1060650|title=Police chief looks back on career while looking forward to retirement|date=September 25, 2018|publisher=Guelph Today|access-date=April 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407182918/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/police-chief-looks-back-on-career-while-looking-forward-to-retirement-1060650|archive-date=April 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Facilities for incarceration===\nThe Wellington County Jail (in Late Gothic Revival Style) and the Governor's Residence (in Georgian style) at 74 Woolwich Street were built in 1911; they were designated by the city for \"historic and architectural value\" and as a National Historic Site in 1983. The property is now an Ontario Court of Justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10906&pid=0 |title=County Jail and Governor's Residence |website=Canada's Historic Places |publisher=Parks Canada |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223020428/https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10906&pid=0 |archive-date=February 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  \n  \nGuelph was home to a major correctional institution from 1911 until 2001,<ref name=\"3arrested\">{{cite news |title=Three arrested after breaking into old Guelph jail |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/guelph-correctional-centre-break-and-enter-1.4063757 |date=April 10, 2017 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922123858/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/guelph-correctional-centre-break-and-enter-1.4063757 |archive-date=September 22, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> originally the Ontario Reformatory with subsequent names including Wellington Detention Centre and, after 1972, Guelph Correctional Centre. The first inmates had been transferred to the Guelph reformatory from Toronto's Central Prison when it closed in 1915. By 1910 however, a prison farm beside the Eramosa River had begun receiving prisoners. The farm inmates constructed a concrete bridge, a spur line to the CPR and a wooden trestle bridge. The official opening of the farm was 25 September 1911. By 1912, the various buildings on the site housed 300; the correctional operations on the site were fully operational by 1914. Between 1911 and 1915, prisoners had built the Administration building, the cell blocks, ponds and waterways, dry stone walls, stairs, gates, bridges and terraced gardens. By 1916, this was the largest correctional facility in Ontario, housing 660.<ref name=\"Yorklands\">{{cite web |url=http://yorklandsgreenhub.ca/history/ |title=Historical Timeline of the Ontario Reformatory at Guelph and Guelph Correctional Center |publisher=Yorklands Green Hub |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725062724/http://yorklandsgreenhub.ca/history/ |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-reformatory-lands-in-june-26-photos-639172 |title=Guelph Reformatory Lands in June (26 photos) |first=Rob |last=O'Flanagan |website=Guelphtoday.com |date=June 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707141008/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-reformatory-lands-in-june-26-photos-639172 |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring World War I, the property served as the Guelph Military Convalescent Hospital a convalescent hospital for over 900 veterans, from 1917. The prisoners returned in January 1921.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/2728157-a-gift-to-the-city-prison-labour-created-much-loved-ponds-off-york-road/|title=A gift to the city: Prison labour created much-loved ponds off York Road|date=September 24, 2011|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd.|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203022524/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/2728157-a-gift-to-the-city-prison-labour-created-much-loved-ponds-off-york-road/|archive-date=December 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"3arrested\"/>\n\nThe farm and Reformatory were used to teach inmates useful skills, including agriculture, dry cleaning, metalworking, and other trades. By the late 1940s the facility produced food for all of Ontario's prisons, and also made blankets, wood and metal products; there was a stone quarry stone on site. By 1962 the prison farm accommodated a dairy, piggery, horses, cattle and vegetable farming.<ref name=\"Yorklands\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kitchenerpost.ca/living-story/9489708-flash-from-the-past-the-prison-farm-changes-the-eramosa-river/ |title=Flash From the Past: The Prison Farm changes the Eramosa River |date=July 5, 2019 |first=Cameron |last=Shelley |website=Kitchenerpost.ca |publisher=Metroland Media |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707135800/https://www.kitchenerpost.ca/living-story/9489708-flash-from-the-past-the-prison-farm-changes-the-eramosa-river/ |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The farm area eventually included barns, a woolen mill, abattoir, tailor shop, laundry, bakery, metal shop, broom shop and other facilities. The prison abattoir was eventually sold off and became the privately owned company, later known as Better Beef (purchased by Cargill Canada in 2005), a massive meat processing plant.<ref name=\"YorkBackground\">{{cite web |title=York District Background Report |url=https://guelph.ca/wp-content/uploads/YorkDistrictBackgroundReport.pdf |pages=7, 78 |publisher=City of Guelph |date=March 17, 2005 |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707150521/https://guelph.ca/wp-content/uploads/YorkDistrictBackgroundReport.pdf |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n \nIn 2001, the  Ministry of Correctional Services closed the entire facility; the remaining inmates were transferred to larger jails.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jermalism.blogspot.ca/2013/11/abandonment-issues-ontario-reformatory.html |title=Abandonment Issues: Ontario Reformatory / Guelph Correctional Centre |date=November 27, 2013 |website=jermalism.blogspot.ca |access-date=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203224528/http://jermalism.blogspot.ca/2013/11/abandonment-issues-ontario-reformatory.html |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Afterwards, the property was used for some film shoots and for training emergency personnel. In December 2017, City Council voted to buy 98 hectares (243 acres) for subsequent sale to developers, including the area that was then the Turf Grass research building and the jail farm, the so-called York District Land.<ref name=\"YorkBackground\"/> The actual penal buildings and the land around them were not included in the plan.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7993701-councillors-approve-plan-to-buy-sell-lands-for-guelph-innovation-district/|title=Councillors approve plan to buy, sell lands for Guelph Innovation District|first=Graeme|last=McNaughton|date=December 12, 2017|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|access-date=December 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171217020502/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7993701-councillors-approve-plan-to-buy-sell-lands-for-guelph-innovation-district/|archive-date=December 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7975497-city-of-guelph-looking-to-buy-then-sell-provincial-lands/ |title=City of Guelph looking to buy, then sell provincial lands |first=Graeme |last=McNaughton |date=December 1, 2017 |publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd |work=Guelph Mercury Tribune |access-date=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203015517/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7975497-city-of-guelph-looking-to-buy-then-sell-provincial-lands/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, 328.6 acres of the land, including 100 acres of natural area, still owned by the province, went on sale. The City of Guelph had not bought the site for the planned Guelph Innovation District, as it had initially considered doing, because of the potential financial risk. A rough estimate in 2017 by the City had suggested that the value of the Detention Centre site was roughly $60 million. The property for sale included the Wellington Detention Centre lands and the nearby Turfgrass Institute but not the buildings or land immediately around the former penal institution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-innovation-district-lands-officially-on-the-market-1502630 |title=Guelph Innovation District lands officially on the market |date=June 12, 2019 |first=Tony |last=Saxon |website=Guelphtoday.com |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707143128/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-innovation-district-lands-officially-on-the-market-1502630 |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nFour school boards operate in the city. The [[Upper Grand District School Board]] administers all of Wellington County, as well as adjacent [[Dufferin County]], while the [[Wellington Catholic District School Board]] administers [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] education in Wellington County, including Guelph. The Conseil scolaire de district catholique Centre-Sud offers French First language education for students with parents who had elementary and secondary education in French at \u00c9cole Saint-Ren\u00e9-Goupil. The [[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]], with similar entrance requirements, operates the \u00c9cole \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire L'Odyss\u00e9e. [[Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir]] operates the \u00c9cole \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire catholique Saint-Ren\u00e9-Goupil.\n\nThere are also numerous private schools in Guelph: Cornerstone Canadian Reformed Christian School, Resurrection Christian Academy, Guelph Community Christian School, Guelph Montessori School, Trillium Waldorf School,  Wellington Hall Academy, and Wellington Montessori School, Echo Montessori. An International Baccalaureate Program is available at Guelph C.V.I.\n\n===Secondary schools===\nDue to the presence of two different English school boards, Guelph has numerous elementary and secondary schools. The secondary schools are as follows:\n\n'''Public''':\n*[[Centennial Collegiate Vocational Institute|Centennial C.V.I.]]\n*[[College Heights Collegiate Vocational Institute|College Heights C.V.I.]]\n*[[Guelph Collegiate Vocational Institute|Guelph C.V.I.]]\n*[[John F. Ross Collegiate Vocational Institute|John F. Ross C.V.I.]]\n\n'''Catholic''':\n*[[Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic High School (Guelph, Ontario)|Our Lady of Lourdes C.H.S.]]\n*[[Saint James Catholic High School (Guelph, Ontario)|Saint James C.H.S.]]\n*[[Bishop Macdonell Catholic High School|Bishop Macdonell C.H.S.]]\n*[[St. John Bosco High School]] <ref>{{cite web |title=St John Bosco {{!}} WCDSB |url=https://stjohnbosco.wellingtoncdsb.ca/ |language=en |access-date=October 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016032737/https://stjohnbosco.wellingtoncdsb.ca/ |archive-date=October 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Post-secondary institutions===\n*[[University of Guelph]], (with approximately 25,300 students)<ref name=\"guelph.ca2\"/> is one of Canada's top [[comprehensive university|comprehensive universities]], and home to the [[Ontario Agricultural College]] and the [[Ontario Veterinary College]]. \n*[[Conestoga College]] operates a small campus in Guelph but in late 2019, the College advised the news media that a major expansion was planned. \"Within five or six years, we will have at least 5,000 students there ... [with] full-service programming,\" said College President John Tibbits. At the time, the Guelph campus had approximately 1,000 students.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-conestoga-campus-expected-to-expand-and-quintiple-its-students-in-next-five-years-1954526 |title=Conestoga's Guelph campus targeted for big growth |date=11 December 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today |access-date=15 December 2019 |quote=\"What we want to have is a full-service programming college like we have in Kitchener. Not just social services but information technology, business, applied computer sciences, health\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215172748/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/guelph-conestoga-campus-expected-to-expand-and-quintiple-its-students-in-next-five-years-1954526 |archive-date=December 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Public library system===\n[[File:Guelph Public Library Old.jpg|thumb|The original [[Carnegie library]] in Guelph.]]\nAlthough a private library, run by the Farmers and Mechanics Institute, existed since 1832, a public library did not open in Guelph until 1882, when the ''[[Free Libraries Act]]'' allowed municipalities to operate libraries. After occupying premises near City Hall, it moved into an [[Carnegie library|Andrew Carnegie-funded]] building in 1905.<ref name=\"GPLhistory\">{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://www.guelphpl.ca/en/about-us/about-us.aspx |publisher=Guelph Public Library |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724164639/https://www.guelphpl.ca/en/about-us/about-us.aspx |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }} Section: Our History, click \"Explore our history through the years\"</ref> The neo-classical (Beaux Art) structure, had been designed in 1902 by W. Frye Colwill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guelphpostcards.blogspot.ca/2013/12/the-carnegie-library.html|title=The Carnegie Library|website=guelphpostcards.blogspot.ca|access-date=January 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027232409/http://guelphpostcards.blogspot.ca/2013/12/the-carnegie-library.html|archive-date=October 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The collection of the Farmers and Mechanics Institute library was contributed to the new library.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.guelphpl.ca/about/history.cfm |title=History |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630062733/https://www.guelphpl.ca/about/history.cfm |archivedate=June 30, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe current main library building of the [[Guelph Public Library]], on Norfolk St. was opened in 1965.<ref name=\"GPLhistory\"/> Guelph is served by a growing library system composed of a main library located in the [[downtown Guelph|downtown]] core, five branches and a [[Bookmobile]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Library Locations and Hours |url=https://www.guelphpl.ca/en/about-us/library-locations-and-hours.aspx |publisher=Guelph Public Library |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724164646/https://www.guelphpl.ca/en/about-us/library-locations-and-hours.aspx |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  With a membership of over 85,000, the [[Guelph Public Library]] system's goals include preserving and indexing public materials relating to the history of Guelph.  Although no formal program has been developed, the library acquires municipal records of archival value from the City of Guelph.<ref>{{cite web |title=Collections |url=https://www.guelphpl.ca/en/collections/collections.aspx |publisher=Guelph Public Library |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724164657/https://www.guelphpl.ca/en/collections/collections.aspx |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA new library location has been discussed since 2018 as part of the redeveloped area downtown, known as the Baker District.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guelph.ca/2017/07/city-pursue-baker-district-redevelopment-proposals/|title=City to pursue Baker District redevelopment proposals|publisher=City of Guelph|date=July 18, 2017|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326142920/http://guelph.ca/2017/07/city-pursue-baker-district-redevelopment-proposals/|archive-date=March 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guelphtoday.com\"/> No decision had been made on the library as of January 2020. The project, estimated at $67.1 million, was to be considered as part of the 2021 City budget which was expected to come to a vote in late 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/9793829-a-few-things-to-expect-from-guelph-city-hall-in-2020/|title=A few things to expect from Guelph City Hall in 2020|publisher=Guelph Mercury|date=January 2, 2020|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104172614/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/9793829-a-few-things-to-expect-from-guelph-city-hall-in-2020/|archive-date=January 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\nThe City of Guelph operates Guelph Museums, including the Guelph Civic Museum which showcases the city's history with exhibits, an interactive gallery and special events; this facility has some 30,000 artifacts. Since 1983 when the city took over this facility, the Civic Museum has also operated [[McCrae House]], the birthplace of Lieutenant-Colonel John McCrae (1872-1918), author of [[In Flanders Fields]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guelphmuseums.ca/venue/mccrae-house/ |title=McCrae House |website=Guelph Museums |publisher=City of Guelph |access-date=November 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113004212/http://guelphmuseums.ca/venue/mccrae-house/ |archive-date=November 13, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Museum also arranged for the restoration and placement of Locomotive 6167, a 1940s steam engine, which is located at the Guelph Central Station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guelphmuseums.ca/venue/locomotive-6167/ |title=Locomotive 6167 |website=Guelph Museums |publisher=City of Guelph |access-date=November 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111215649/http://guelphmuseums.ca/venue/locomotive-6167/ |archive-date=November 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Medical facilities===\nThe city currently has one hospital, [[Guelph General Hospital|Guelph General]], which is rated as one of the safest in Canada in terms of the hospital standardized mortality ratio; the lower the better. Guelph's facility had a score of 78 in 2017, notably better than the national average of 91. By comparison, Cambridge Memorial Hospital had a score of 95.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7973917-region-s-hospitals-rank-well-on-patient-safety-indicator/|title=Region\u2019s hospitals rank well on patient safety indicator|first=Johanna|last=Weidner|date=December 1, 2017|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd.|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203015813/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7973917-region-s-hospitals-rank-well-on-patient-safety-indicator/|archive-date=December 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> St. Joseph's Health Centre was previously a hospital, but is now a 240-bed long-term care home with a 91-bed specialty unit for complex continuing, rehabilitation and palliative care. Various outpatient services are also provided at this facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwhealthline.ca/displayservice.aspx?id=102576|title=St Joseph's Health Centre Guelph|website=Thehealthline.ca|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929204834/http://wwhealthline.ca/displayservice.aspx?id=102576|archive-date=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnother major facility, Homewood Health Centre offers treatment for mental health and addiction issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.homewoodhealth.com/health-centre/programs/overview |title=Homewood Health Centre programs and services |publisher=Homewood Health, Inc. |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623024808/http://www.homewoodhealth.com/health-centre/programs/overview |archive-date=June 23, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The facility was founded in 1883 by the Homewood Retreat Association of Guelph as \"a private asylum for the Insane and an Asylum for Inebriates\" on a 19-acre property which included the Donald Guthrie house. The first patients were admitted in December of that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ao.minisisinc.com/scripts/mwimain.dll/144/ARCH_AUTHORITY/AUTH_DESC_DET_REP/SISN+7304?SESSIONSEARCH |title=Homewood Sanitarium |website=Archives of Ontario |publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326064336/http://ao.minisisinc.com/scripts/mwimain.dll/144/ARCH_AUTHORITY/AUTH_DESC_DET_REP/SISN+7304?SESSIONSEARCH |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHomewood grew to a 312-bed mental and behavioural health facility and also formed a partnership with R.B. Schlegel Holdings Inc.to operate Oakwood Retirement Communities Inc., a long-term care facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guelph.ca/wp-content/uploads/Guelph-APeoplesHeritage.pdf |title=Guelph: A People's Heritage 1827-2002 |first=Hilary |last=Stead |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515011615/http://guelph.ca/wp-content/uploads/Guelph-APeoplesHeritage.pdf |archive-date=May 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}, Homewood Corp. advertisement: \"Caring for Guelph, Caring for Canada\"</ref>\n\n===Transportation===\n====Bus====\n{{Main|Guelph Transit}}\n[[Guelph Transit]] provides local transportation around the city. On June 20, 2007, Guelph Transit launched a web-based system known as ''Next Bus''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guelph.ca/living.cfm?subCatID=1736&smocid=2312 |title=When's the Next Bus? |publisher=Guelph.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208021807/http://www.guelph.ca/living.cfm?subCatID=1736&smocid=2312 |archive-date=February 8, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Global positioning satellite]]s (GPS) technology and advanced computer modelling provide riders via the Internet, [[handheld device]]s (including [[Palm Pilot|Palms]], [[BlackBerry|Blackberries]], and Web-capable [[cellular phone]]s), or their telephones to receive accurate, real-time arrival and departure information.  Intercity connections by [[GO Transit]] and [[Greyhound Canada]] are made at the [[Guelph Central Station]] and University of Guelph.\n\n====Rail====\n[[File:Guelph Railway Station 2015.jpg|thumb|Guelph Central train station]]\nGuelph was the first municipality in Canada to have its own federally chartered railway, the [[Guelph Junction Railway]]. This 25 kilometre (16 miles) link to the CPR is still municipally owned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guelph Junction Railway |url=http://guelph.ca/business/economic-development-office/guelph-junction-railway/ |publisher=City of Guelph |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721170645/http://guelph.ca/business/economic-development-office/guelph-junction-railway/ |archive-date=July 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBuilt in 1911, the [[Guelph Central Station]] (still in use), was constructed by the [[Grand Trunk Railway]] which had arrived in Guelph in 1856;<ref name=\"guelphmercury.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7250489-guelph-central-station-is-officially-reopened/|title=Guelph Central Station is officially reopened|first=Chris|last=Seto|date=April 19, 2017|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005055045/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/7250489-guelph-central-station-is-officially-reopened/|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> years later, it was taken over by the [[Canadian National Railway]].  It is a classic example of early 20th Century Canadian railway station design and has been designated as a heritage structure under the ''[[Heritage Railway Stations Protection Act]]''.<ref name=fact-sheet>{{cite web |url=http://guelph.ca/2017/04/fact-sheet-guelph-central-train-station/ |title=Fact sheet: Guelph Central Train Station|date=April 11, 2017 |publisher=City of Guelph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005051903/http://guelph.ca/2017/04/fact-sheet-guelph-central-train-station/ |archivedate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Guelph Train Station |publisher=Ontario Heritage Trust |url=https://www.heritagetrust.on.ca/en/oha/details?id=23&backlinkslug=search-results&fields%5Blocation%5D=50%2C150&fields%5Bheritage_function_category%5D=15 |website=Ontario Heritage Act Register |accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> The Romanesque Revival building, with its Italianate tower, has been listed on the Canadian Register since 2006 and was formally recognized as one of Canada's Historic Places in November 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=4569|title=Former Canadian National Railways (VIA Rail/GO Transit) Station|website=www.historicplaces.ca|publisher=Parks Canada|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223125222/http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=4569|archive-date=December 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A renovation project in 2016-2017 provided various benefits, including repairs to maintain and restore heritage aspects.<ref name=\"guelphmercury.com\"/>\n\nThere had also been passenger stations in Guelph that were built by the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]].<ref name=\"CPRfinalstop\">{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/living-story/4896449-cpr-station-s-final-stop-mystery/ |title=CPR station\u2019s final stop mystery |first=Bill |last=Bean |date=October 3, 2014 |publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd |work=Guelph Mercury Tribune |access-date=July 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005055504/https://www.guelphmercury.com/living-story/4896449-cpr-station-s-final-stop-mystery/ |archive-date=October 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first CPR station, from the 1800s, was the Priory House station, converted from the first house in Guelph. It stood opposite the current Priory Square and was eventually dismantled.<ref name=\"therecord.com\"/> Its replacement, located between Cardigan Street and the Speed River, was a brick building erected in 1911.<ref name=\"virtualreferencelibrary.ca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://guelphpostcards.blogspot.ca/2017/05/the-arrival-of-guelph-central-station.html|title=The arrival of Guelph Central Station, 1911|website=guelphpostcards.blogspot.ca|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005051516/http://guelphpostcards.blogspot.ca/2017/05/the-arrival-of-guelph-central-station.html|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"therecord.com\"/><ref name=\"virtualreferencelibrary.ca\"/> After this brick building was no longer used as a rail station, it was converted for other purposes; eventually it was moved to the Galt area of [[Cambridge, Ontario]].<ref name=\"CPRfinalstop\"/>\n\nThe Central station is currently an Intermodal Transit Terminal that includes bus and railway services in one facility. The following is a summary of its purpose from an April 2017 report:\n \n\"Guelph Central Train Station is a busy transit hub that accommodates Guelph Transit, GO Transit, Via Rail and Greyhound Canada operations. Each weekday, more than 5,000 passengers board Guelph Transit, to travel on one of the 15 different routes that operate out of the bus bays adjacent to the train station.\"<ref name=fact-sheet/>\n\n====Highways====\n*[[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] to Toronto and London.\n*[[Ontario Highway 7|Highway 7]] to Kitchener and [[Acton, Ontario|Acton]].  The MTO has commenced construction of the Hanlon link to [[Kitchener, Ontario]], a [[controlled-access highway]] running parallel to the existing Highway 7 from the Hanlon Expressway to Kitchener.<ref>{{cite news |title=MTO says new Highway 7 build has begun |url=http://www.therecord.com/news-story/5785630-mto-says-new-highway-7-build-has-begun/ |journal=Waterloo Region Record |author=Rob O'Flanagan |date=August 5, 2015 |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418035546/http://www.therecord.com/news-story/5785630-mto-says-new-highway-7-build-has-begun/ |archive-date=April 18, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Ontario Highway 6|Highway 6]] to Hamilton and Owen Sound. This highway is known as the [[Hanlon Parkway|Hanlon Expressway]] for most of its length inside the city.\n\n==Government==\n\n===Municipal===\n{{Main|Guelph City Council}}\n\nThe city is a single-tier municipality governed by a mayor-council system. The structure of the municipal government is stipulated by the [[Ontario Municipal Act]] of 2001. There are currently 12 councillors and a mayor, with two councillors representing each of the six wards.\n\nThe mayor and members of the city council serve four-year terms without term limits, with the next election in October 2022. Prior to the [[Guelph municipal election, 2006|2006 election]], the mayor and city councillors served three-year terms.\n\n[[Guelph City Council]] is responsible for policy and decision making, monitoring the operation and performance of the city, analyzing and approving budgets and determining spending priorities.\n\nIn [[2018 Ontario municipal elections#Guelph|2018]], incumbent Mayor [[Cam Guthrie]] was re-elected with 66.6% of the vote.\n\n===Provincial===\n{{Main|Guelph (provincial electoral district)}}\n\nAs of the 2018 election, Guelph occupies a single provincial riding of the same name, and is currently represented in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] by [[Mike Schreiner]], the current leader of [[Ontario Green Party]].\n\n===Federal===\n{{Main|Guelph (electoral district)}}\nGuelph also occupies a federal riding of the same name.  The member of Parliament is [[Lloyd Longfield]] of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]].\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Church of Our Lady, Guelph, Ontario, from rivers confluence.jpg|thumb|Basilica of Our Lady Immaculate, above city]]\n[[File:Riparian restoration, Speed River.jpg|thumb|Riparian restoration]]\n\n===Historic sites===\n*[[Downtown Guelph]]: Several downtown streets are lined with [[Victorian Architecture|Victorian era]] buildings, which are now well over a century old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guelpharts.ca/historical-walking-tours-return-for-august|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203013846/https://guelpharts.ca/historical-walking-tours-return-for-august |archivedate=December 3, 2017 |title=Historical Walking Tours Return for August |publisher=Guelph Arts Council }}</ref> Many of Guelph's historically designated properties are in or near the downtown area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://guelph.ca/city-hall/planning-and-development/community-plans-studies/heritage-conservation/designated-properties/ |title=Designated heritage properties |publisher=City of Guelph |access-date=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203015342/https://guelph.ca/city-hall/planning-and-development/community-plans-studies/heritage-conservation/designated-properties/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The old City Hall on Carden St., built between 1856 and 1857, is a National Historic Site of Canada; this structure is an example of mid-19th century Renaissance Revival architecture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10090 |title=Guelph City Hall |website=www.historicplaces.ca |publisher=Parks Canada |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203082814/http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10090 |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> This building, as well as its Annex built circa 1865, are also historically designated by the province. Other historically designated buildings in the area include the Winter Fair Building, the County Jail and Governor's Residence<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10906&pid=0 |title=County Jail and Governor's Residence |website=www.historicplaces.ca |publisher=Parks Canada |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223020428/https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10906&pid=0 |archive-date=February 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Guelph Armoury. The [[Old Quebec Street Mall]] was a street built in the 1800s that was enclosed and covered; that work was completed in 1984 and the street has become an indoor shopping mall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://oldquebecstreet.com/quebec-street-mall-guelph/quebec-street-mall-history-guelph/ |title=Old Quebec Street Mall in Guelph |publisher=Downtown Guelph BIA |access-date=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203021933/http://oldquebecstreet.com/quebec-street-mall-guelph/quebec-street-mall-history-guelph/ |archive-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Guelph Civic Museum Dusk 2016.jpg|thumb|Guelph Civic Museum]]\n*The [[Guelph Civic Museum]] has been located on \"Catholic Hill\" (Norfolk St. and Cork St.) adjacent to the Basilica of Our Lady Immaculate since 2012, moving to this location from a nationally designated historic site at 6 Dublin St. South.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guelph.ca/location/dublin-street-south-6/|title=Dublin Street South - 6|publisher=City of Guelph|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221337/https://guelph.ca/location/dublin-street-south-6/|archive-date=September 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10097 |title=Guelph Civic Museum |website=www.historicplaces.ca |publisher=Parks Canada |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915005631/http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=10097 |archive-date=September 15, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The museum has a collection of pictures, films and other antique materials related to the historical development of the City of Guelph.\n*Among the oldest of the city's neighbourhoods, settled by affluent citizens, the St. George's Park area features heritage homes and mansions in the highest part of Guelph. Much of the city's elite lived on the hill running up Grange Street and many of the homes have been renovated.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/in-your-neighbourhood-st-georges-park-15-photos-569624 |title=In Your Neighbourhood: St. George's Park (15 Photos) |date=March 23, 2017 |first=Rob |last=O'Flanagan |website=Guelphtoday.com |access-date=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204114532/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/in-your-neighbourhood-st-georges-park-15-photos-569624 |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Exhibition Park neighbourhood, containing the oldest park in Guelph, is an area that was settled in the 1870s and still contains many Victorian style heritage homes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/in-your-neighbourhood-exhibition-park-34-photos-605083 |title=In Your Neighbourhood: Exhibition Park (34 Photos) |date=May 7, 2017 |first=Rob |last=O'Flanagan |website=Guelphtoday.com |access-date=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204114527/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/in-your-neighbourhood-exhibition-park-34-photos-605083 |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The Brooklyn and College Hill area south of the Speed River<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/early-guelph-neighbourhood-gets-heritage-designation-1.3415214|title=Early Guelph neighbourhood gets heritage designation|date=January 22, 2016|first=Kate|last=Bueckert|publisher=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412111458/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/early-guelph-neighbourhood-gets-heritage-designation-1.3415214|archive-date=April 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> is the city's only district that was designated under the Ontario Heritage Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guelph.ca/city-hall/planning-and-development/community-plans-studies/heritage-conservation/heritage-studies/|title=Heritage Conservation District|publisher=City of Guelph|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203155313/https://guelph.ca/city-hall/planning-and-development/community-plans-studies/heritage-conservation/heritage-studies/|archive-date=December 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/community-story/5870352-cowan-house-merits-historical-designation/|title=Cowan House merits historical designation|date=March 19, 2015|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203015515/https://www.guelphmercury.com/community-story/5870352-cowan-house-merits-historical-designation/|archive-date=December 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*St. Patrick's Ward (The Ward) with many old buildings, originally contained both manufacturing facilities and modest homes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://guelpharts.ca/images/walkingtours/wardone/Ward-One-Walking--Tour.pdf |title=Ward One Walking Tour |publisher=Guelph Arts Council}}</ref>  Many newcomers from Europe, particularly Italy, settled here after 1850.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/in-your-neighbourhood-the-ward-25-photos-575126|title=In Your Neighbourhood: The Ward (25 photos)|date=March 30, 2017|first=Rob|last=O'Flanagan|website=Guelphtoday.com|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204114534/https://www.guelphtoday.com/local-news/in-your-neighbourhood-the-ward-25-photos-575126|archive-date=December 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Allan's Mill]]\n[[File:Heffernan Street Footbridge, Guelph, ON.jpg|thumb|Heffernan Street Footbridge]]\n* Heffernan Street Footbridge: Spanning the Speed River behind St. George's Anglican Church, this structure was built in 1913, and replaced an earlier steel bridge. The footbridge was designated a heritage site and was restored/reconstructed in 1991 to more closely resemble the original design<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/rooted/the-bridge-that-spans-generations-1949162 |title=The bridge that spans generations |date=11 December 2019 |publisher=Guelph Today |access-date=11 December 2019 |quote=a historic stroll over Speed River on the Heffernan Street Footbridge |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211194530/https://www.guelphtoday.com/rooted/the-bridge-that-spans-generations-1949162 |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Goldie Mill ruins: Once owned by the Goldie family, an important name in the early Waterloo Region, the mill was operated from 1866 until 1953 when a fire destroyed it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/community-story/7805210-city-of-guelph-looks-to-historically-designate-mid-19th-century-tavern/|title=City of Guelph looks to historically designate mid-19th century tavern|date=November 6, 2017|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|access-date=December 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203021316/https://www.guelphmercury.com/community-story/7805210-city-of-guelph-looks-to-historically-designate-mid-19th-century-tavern/|archive-date=December 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> For some years, it served as a venue for outdoor public and private events but the area around the buildings was closed to the public in June 2017 due to soil contamination and sinkholes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guelph.ca/location/goldie-mill-park/|title=Goldie Mill Park and ruins|publisher=City of Guelph|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123121832/http://guelph.ca/location/goldie-mill-park/|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Restoration of the ruins was underway in 2019, authorized by the owner, the [[Grand River Conservation Authority]]; the site was expected to re-open to the public in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/9279759-guelph-s-goldie-mill-could-reopen-in-2020/|title=Guelph's Goldie Mill could reopen in 2020|publisher=Guelph Mercury|accessdate=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413135402/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/9279759-guelph-s-goldie-mill-could-reopen-in-2020/|archive-date=April 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Guelph Public Library]] was the first public library established in Ontario under the Public Library Act of 1882.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtc.gov.on.ca/en/libraries/libraries.shtml |title=Ontario Public Libraries |date=28 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n====National Historic Sites====\nNationally designated sites in the city include:\n*[[Old City Hall (Guelph)|Old City Hall]], a formal, classical civic building; built in 1856\u201357.\n*[[McCrae House]], home of [[John McCrae]], author of \"[[In Flanders Fields]]\", built in 1858.\n*[[Basilica of Our Lady Immaculate]], a Roman Catholic church designed by [[Joseph Connolly (architect)|Joseph Connolly]], located downtown, is a local landmark and a National Historic Site. The church was built over a number of years, specifically 1876 to 1888.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=7646 |title=Our Lady of the Immaculate Conception National Historic Site of Canada |website=www.historicplaces.ca |publisher=Parks Canada |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929040058/https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=7646 |archive-date=September 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Outdoor attractions===\n\nMost of the natural attractions of Guelph are located beside the two rivers which pass inside the city, Speed River and Eramosa River.\n*[[Guelph Lake]]\n*[[University of Guelph Arboretum]]\n*Riverside Park, located beside the Speed River at the north of Guelph\n*York Road Park\n*Hanlon Creek Park (Preservation Park)\n*Royal City Park and Wellington Street nature sites\n\n===Festivals===\n*Guelph Contemporary Dance Festival<ref>{{cite web |title=Festival |url=https://www.guelphdance.ca/festival/ |publisher=Guelph Dance |accessdate=July 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723125546/https://www.guelphdance.ca/festival/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Guelph Pride]] and Winter Pride<ref>{{cite web |title=Guelph Pride |url=https://guelphpride.com/ |accessdate=July 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170114170554/http://guelphpride.com/ |archive-date=January 14, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Guelph and District Multicultural Festival<ref>{{cite web |title=Guelph & District Multicultural Festival |url=http://gdmf.ca/ |accessdate=July 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723125547/http://gdmf.ca/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Hillside Festival]]\n* Two Rivers Festival\n* John Galt Day\n* Guelph Jazz Festival\n* Guelph Festival of Moving Media\n* [[Guelph Film Festival]]\n* Vegfest Guelph\n\n===Arts facilities===\n*The [[Art Gallery of Guelph]], formerly Macdonald Stewart Art Centre<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artgalleryofguelph.ca/ |title=Art Gallery of Guelph |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723120833/http://artgalleryofguelph.ca/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*The Bookshelf Ebar Art Space\n*[[Ed Video Media Arts Centre]]\n*[[River Run Centre]]\n* Guelph Youth Music Centre<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gymc.ca/ |title=Guelph Youth Music Centre |accessdate=February 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130122931/http://www.gymc.ca/ |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n\n{{Main|Media in Guelph}}\n\nThe earliest newspaper published in Guelph was the ''Guelph Herald'', which lasted for nine months after it was started in 1842 by Charles McDonnell. The ''Wellingtonian'' also lasted for only a short time in 1843.  The next one to be published was ''The Advertiser'' in 1845. In 1847, the new ''Guelph Herald'' was established as a weekly.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.electricscotland.com/canada/guelph/guelphbook.pdf|title=Guelph: A People's Heritage 1827-2002|first=Hilary|last=Stead|page=13|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302021902/https://www.electricscotland.com/Canada/guelph/guelphbook.pdf|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBoth of those publications disappeared but the city was served by a daily newspaper for 149 years until the [[Guelph Mercury]] ceased operations in January 2016 due to declining subscriptions and revenues.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/guelph-mercury-to-close-amid-financial-pressures/article28370737/ |title=Guelph Mercury newspaper to close amid financial pressures |date=January 25, 2016 |first1=Tim |last1=Shufelt |first2=Christine |last2=Dobby |publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]] |access-date=July 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316053324/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/guelph-mercury-to-close-amid-financial-pressures/article28370737// |archive-date=March 16, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the time, it was owned by [[Metroland Media Group]] which also owned the Guelph Tribune, a twice weekly publication with limited news coverage. The latter increased its reporting of local news, assumed publication of the Guelph and District Homes section and, in April 2016, took over operation of the Mercury website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/6247549-guelph-mercury-quits-print-editions/|title=Guelph Mercury quits print editions|date=January 25, 2016|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316205508/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/6247549-guelph-mercury-quits-print-editions/|archive-date=March 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the same time, the newspaper re-branded with a new title, [[Guelph Mercury Tribune]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/6517328-welcome-to-the-new-guelph-mercury-tribune-/|title=Welcome to the new Guelph Mercury Tribune!|date=April 28, 2016|publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd|work=Guelph Mercury Tribune|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316205511/https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/6517328-welcome-to-the-new-guelph-mercury-tribune-/|archive-date=March 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Village Media]] publishes a website called ''Guelph Today'', which provides news and other information about special events and local businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphtoday.com/about-guelphtoday|title=About GuelphToday.com|access-date=July 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604074531/https://www.guelphtoday.com/about-guelphtoday|archive-date=June 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe city is served by two radio stations: \n*Magic 106.1, [[CIMJ-FM]], featuring [[hot adult contemporary]] music branded as Today's Best Mix \n*[[CJOY]], 1460, broadcasting an [[oldies]] format and branded as Greatest Hits\nBoth stations have been owned by [[Corus Entertainment]] since 2000. The [[University of Guelph]] station 93.3 [[CFRU-FM]], Campus and Community Radio, has been broadcasting since 1980, currently at 250 watts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfru.ca/about-us|title=CFRU 93.3 FM|publisher=CFRU|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009114203/http://www.cfru.ca/about-us/|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRadio stations from Kitchener-Waterloo and CTV Kitchener, [[CKCO-DT]] television, also provide some coverage of Guelph news.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kitchener.foundlocally.com/Communications/MediaFMRadio.htm|title=Kitchener-Waterloo Ontario Broadcast FM Radio Stations information, listings and links|website=kitchener.foundlocally.com|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708180041/http://kitchener.foundlocally.com/Communications/MediaFMRadio.htm|archive-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kitchener.foundlocally.com/Communications/MediaAMRadio.htm|title=Kitchener-Waterloo Ontario Broadcast AM Radio Stations information, listings and links|website=kitchener.foundlocally.com|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708193052/http://kitchener.foundlocally.com/Communications/MediaAMRadio.htm|archive-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Since 2011, CKCO has not been identified by its call letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ckco-history.com/history/|title=History \u00ab|website=ckco-history.com|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708173653/http://ckco-history.com/history/|archive-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/television/ckco-dt|title=CKCO-DT - History of Canadian Broadcasting|website=www.broadcasting-history.ca|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814223226/http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/television/ckco-dt|archive-date=August 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Entertainment===\nThe [[Sleeman Centre (Guelph)|Sleeman Centre]] is a sports and entertainment venue in Guelph. The large, modern facility allows for a variety of events such as concerts, sporting and family events, trade shows and conferences, and it is home to the local hockey team, the [[Guelph Storm]].<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=http://thesleemancentre.com/about-us/ |publisher=Sleeman Centre |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724231604/http://thesleemancentre.com/about-us/ |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nFrom a Bell Organ factory to the opera singer [[Edward Johnson (tenor)|Edward Johnson]], Guelph has been a source of musical contribution. Today, Guelph has a thriving [[indie rock]] scene, which has spawned some of Canada's more well-known indie bands, many of which are highlighted in the annual Kazoo Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ontheaside.com/uncategorized/guelphs-kazoo-makes-a-compelling-case-for-small-music-festivals/ |title=Guelph\u2019s Kazoo! makes a compelling case for small music festivals |publisher=Michael Rancic, A.Side |date= |accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref> <!--PLEASE SEE TALK BEFORE ADDING A BAND--> Guelph is also home to the [[Hillside Festival]], a hugely popular music festival held at nearby [[Guelph Lake]] during the summer, as well as the Guelph Jazz Festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guelphjazzfestival.com/ |title=Guelph Jazz Festival |publisher=Guelph Jazz Festival |date= |accessdate=February 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302205101/http://www.guelphjazzfestival.com/ |archive-date=March 2, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGuelph is also home to the Guelph Symphony Orchestra,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guelphsymphony.com/ |title=Guelph Symphony Orchestra |publisher=Guelph Symphony Orchestra |accessdate=January 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112133347/http://www.guelphsymphony.com/ |archive-date=January 12, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and two yearly [[classical music]] festivals. The Kiwanis Music Festival of Guelph showcases students from Guelph and surrounding areas,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guelphkiwanismusicfestival.org/ |title=The Kiwanis Music Festival of Guelph |publisher=Kiwanis Club of Guelph |date= |accessdate=January 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107042433/http://guelphkiwanismusicfestival.org/ |archive-date=January 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> while the Guelph Musicfest offers performances by local professional classical musicians.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artset.net/guelphmusicfest/ |title=The Kiwanis Music Festival of Guelph |publisher=Guelph Musicfest |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112135115/http://artset.net/guelphmusicfest/ |archive-date=January 12, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Sports teams===\n[[File:Guelph Storm face off.jpg|thumb|The Guelph Storm at [[home ice]] in 2006.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Club\n! scope=\"col\" | League\n! scope=\"col\" | Sport\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Established\n! scope=\"col\" | Championships\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Storm]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League]]\n| Hockey\n| [[Sleeman Centre (Guelph)|Sleeman Centre]]\n| 1991 <br /> \n| 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Royals (baseball)|Guelph Royals]]\n| [[Intercounty Baseball League]]\n| Baseball\n| [[Hastings Stadium|David E. Hastings Stadium at Exhibition Park]]\n| 1919\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Gryphons]]\n| [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport]]\n| University\n| [[W.F. Mitchell Centre]] and Alumni Stadium\n| 1874\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Regals]]\n| [[OLA Junior B Lacrosse League|Ontario Lacrosse Association]]\n| Lacrosse\n| Victoria Road Recreation Centre\n| 1992\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Gryphons FC]]\n| [[Ontario Soccer League]], [[Kitchener and District Soccer League]], [[South West Region Soccer League]]\n| Soccer\n| Centennial Park and Guelph Lake Sports Fields\n| circa 1985\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Nighthawks]]\n| [[Canadian Elite Basketball League]]\n| Basketball\n| [[Sleeman Centre (Guelph)|Sleeman Centre]]\n| 2017\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Jr. Gryphons]]\n| [[Ontario Varsity Football League|Ontario Football Conference]]\n| Football\n| [[University of Guelph]]'s Alumni Stadium\n| 1997\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Guelph Gargoyles]]\n| [[Ontario Australian Football League]]\n| Australian Football\n| Margaret Green Park\n| 2001\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Royal City Roller Derby]]\n| [[Women's Flat Track Derby Association]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wftda.com/leagues |title=Member Leagues - Women\u2019s Flat Track Derby Association |website=Wftda.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519031654/http://wftda.com/leagues |archive-date=May 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Roller Derby\n| Arenas in Guelph (Victoria Road Rec Centre, Exhibition Park, West End Rec Centre)\n| 2010\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: center;\" | [[Speed River Track and Field Club]]\n| [[Athletics Canada]]\n| Athletics\n| Alumni Stadium\n| 1997\n| 10\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Guelph}}\n\n==Twin cities==\n* {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Castelfranco Veneto]], [[Italy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comune.castelfrancoveneto.tv.it/index.php?area=14&menu=67&page=585|title=Gemellaggio con la citt\u00e0 di Guelph - Comune Castelfranco Veneto|first=Q-Web|last=srl|website=www.comune.castelfrancoveneto.tv.it|access-date=February 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228041449/https://www.comune.castelfrancoveneto.tv.it/index.php?area=14&menu=67&page=585|archive-date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"SC11\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3523008&Geo2=CD&Code2=3523&Data=Count&SearchText=guelph&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=\n |title=Guelph (city) community profile\n |work=[[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census data]]\n |publisher=Statistics Canada\n |access-date=February 10, 2012\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220213602/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3523008&Geo2=CD&Code2=3523&Data=Count&SearchText=guelph&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=\n |archive-date=February 20, 2014\n |url-status=live\n }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Guelph}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Guelph}}\n*[http://www.guelph.ca/ City of Guelph]\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Guelph\n| North     = [[Guelph/Eramosa, Ontario|Guelph/Eramosa]]\n| Northeast = [[Guelph/Eramosa, Ontario|Guelph/Eramosa]]\n| East      = [[Guelph/Eramosa, Ontario|Guelph/Eramosa]]\n| Southeast = \n| South     = [[Puslinch, Ontario|Puslinch]]\n| Southwest = [[Puslinch, Ontario|Puslinch]]\n| West      = \n| Northwest = \n}}\n{{Guelph}}\n{{Wellington County}}\n{{Subdivisions of Ontario}}\n{{Census metropolitan areas by size}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1827 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Guelph| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1827]]\n[[Category:Single-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Southwestern Ontario]]\n[[Category:1820s establishments in Upper Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the city|the electoral district|Guelph (electoral district)|other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Guelph\n| official_name          = City of Guelph\n| native_name            = \n| settlement_type        = [[List of cities in Ontario|City]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Single-tier municipalities|single-tier]])\n| image_skyline          = \n| imagesize              = 300px\n| image_caption   